The filesystem table, for persistent mounts.

A mount you make by hand with the mount command is temporary; it disappears at the next reboot. To make a mount permanent, you add an entry to the filesystem table, the file at slash e-t-c slash f-s-t-a-b. Each line in it has six space-separated fields, and learning them is essential.

The first field is the device, what to mount, and here you should strongly prefer a u-u-i-d over a device name, because device names are unstable. The second is the mount point, where to attach it, which must already exist. The third is the type, the filesystem kind, such as e-x-t-four or swap. The fourth is the options, the same comma-separated mount options you would pass by hand, with the word defaults for ordinary use. The fifth field is the dump field, a leftover from an old backup tool, which today you simply always set to zero. And the sixth is the pass field, which controls the order of the boot-time filesystem check: one for the root filesystem, two for other filesystems, and zero to skip checking, as you do for swap and network filesystems.

There is a critical safety habit here. After editing the filesystem table, always test it before rebooting. Running mount with the dash a flag mounts everything in the table that is not already mounted, and the verify option checks the file's syntax. If that test reports an error, you must fix it before you reboot, because a broken filesystem table can drop the machine into emergency mode at the next boot, with no easy way back. The wise pattern when adding a new entry is to mount it by hand first to confirm it works, unmount it, add the line to the table, run mount dash a to test that line, and only then reboot once you are confident.
